---
import Primer from '../../layouts/Primer.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';
---
<Primer
  title="Atoms as a Graph"
  eyebrow="A Primer on Matter Models · Chapter Two"
  deck="How do you hand a pile of atoms to a function at all? Two ideas — locality and symmetry — turn the question into something a machine can learn."
  running="Ch. 2 — Atoms as a Graph"
  prev={{ href: url('/primer/the-surface'), label: 'The Surface Beneath Everything' }}
  next={{ href: url('/primer/inside-the-network'), label: 'Inside the Network' }}
>
  <p class="lead">
    You have a function to build. It eats an arrangement of atoms and returns one energy. The
    obvious way to hand it the atoms is to give it their coordinates — a long list of (x, y, z)
    triples, one per atom — and train a network to turn that list into the energy.
  </p>

  <p>
    It fails at once. Pick the whole molecule up and set it down a step to the left. Every coordinate
    in the list changes; the energy does not. Turn the molecule forty degrees. Every coordinate
    changes; the energy does not. Swap the labels on two identical atoms — what was atom 5 is now
    atom 12 — and once more every number moves while the energy sits still. A network fed raw
    coordinates would have to learn by brute force that all these different-looking lists mean one
    energy. It is like grading an essay from the pixel positions of the ink: nudge the page and the
    meaning you learned is gone.
  </p>

  <p>
    Three changes, then, must leave the energy untouched: sliding the whole system (a
    <strong>translation</strong>), turning it (a <strong>rotation</strong>), and relabeling identical
    atoms (a <strong>permutation</strong>). A change that leaves the energy untouched is called a
    <strong>symmetry</strong> of it — these are the energy's three. A description that already obeys
    all three is worth far more than one the network must learn to ignore. The rest of this chapter
    builds that description out of two ideas: <strong>locality</strong> and <strong>symmetry</strong>.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 1</span>Locality: chop the energy into pieces</h2>

  <p>
    Start with locality, the idea Chapter 1 promised and then set aside. An atom's share of the
    energy depends almost entirely on what sits near it. The atoms across the room barely register.
  </p>

  <p>
    So chop the energy into per-atom pieces. Write the total as a sum,
    <em>E</em> = Σ<sub>i</sub> ε<sub>i</sub>: the energy <em>E</em> is the sum, over every atom
    <em>i</em>, of a per-atom energy ε<sub>i</sub>. And let each ε<sub>i</sub> depend only on the
    atoms within a fixed cutoff distance of atom <em>i</em>. Every atom looks around its own
    neighborhood, contributes its piece, and the pieces add up.
  </p>

  <p>
    Picture a stadium crowd whose total noise you want to measure. You do not need a microphone that
    hears the whole stadium. Give each person a small meter that picks up only their nearest
    neighbors, read all the meters, and add them. The same per-person rule works whether the crowd
    is ten people or ten thousand.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <div class="fig-frame">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 290" role="img" aria-label="The total energy written as a sum of per-atom energies, each computed from one atom's local neighborhood.">
        <g stroke="var(--rule)" stroke-width="1">
          <line x1="120" y1="80" x2="170" y2="70" />
          <line x1="120" y1="80" x2="150" y2="130" />
          <line x1="170" y1="70" x2="200" y2="135" />
          <line x1="150" y1="130" x2="200" y2="135" />
          <line x1="150" y1="130" x2="105" y2="150" />
          <line x1="150" y1="130" x2="165" y2="185" />
          <line x1="200" y1="135" x2="225" y2="185" />
        </g>
        <circle cx="150" cy="130" r="68" fill="none" stroke="var(--oxblood)" stroke-width="1" stroke-dasharray="3 3" />
        <g fill="var(--ink)">
          <circle cx="120" cy="80" r="6.5" />
          <circle cx="170" cy="70" r="6.5" />
          <circle cx="200" cy="135" r="6.5" />
          <circle cx="105" cy="150" r="6.5" />
          <circle cx="165" cy="185" r="6.5" />
          <circle cx="225" cy="185" r="6.5" />
        </g>
        <circle cx="150" cy="130" r="7.5" fill="var(--oxblood)" />
        <text x="150" y="214" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">atom i and the neighbors inside its cutoff</text>

        <line x1="252" y1="120" x2="332" y2="120" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.2" marker-end="url(#g1arr)" />
        <text x="292" y="110" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">look around</text>

        <rect x="346" y="98" width="116" height="46" fill="none" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1" />
        <text x="404" y="120" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif" style="font-size:17px;">εᵢ</text>
        <text x="404" y="137" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">atom i's piece</text>

        <line x1="40" y1="238" x2="680" y2="238" stroke="var(--rule)" stroke-width="0.5" stroke-dasharray="2 4" />
        <text x="360" y="266" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif" style="font-size:18px;">E = ε₁ + ε₂ + ε₃ + ⋯ + εₙ</text>

        <defs>
          <marker id="g1arr" markerWidth="9" markerHeight="9" refX="7" refY="4.5" orient="auto"><path d="M0 0 L9 4.5 L0 9 z" fill="var(--ink)" /></marker>
        </defs>
      </svg>
    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 1</span>Each atom looks only at the neighbors inside its cutoff and contributes one number, ε<sub>i</sub>; the total energy is those numbers added up.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    The payoff is <strong>reach</strong>. Because the rule for ε<sub>i</sub> is the same for every
    atom of a given element and looks only at a local patch — the atoms inside its cutoff — you can
    learn it on small arrangements and apply it to enormous ones: train on a hundred atoms, run on a
    million, no retraining. It also settles the puzzle Chapter 1 left open: the model learns
    patches, never whole arrangements, and a few thousand small structures hold the same handful of
    patches over and over.
  </p>

  <p>
    Locality is an approximation, and on its face a drastic one — an atom's world, cut off at a
    radius. In practice the energy it discards beyond a few ångströms (Å) — an ångström is about an
    atom's width — usually amounts to a few thousandths of an electron-volt (eV) per atom in
    well-behaved systems, negligible against the eV-scale energies that make and break bonds. But
    not every system is well-behaved. Pull an electron off one end of a long molecule and the energy
    shifts at the far end, past any cutoff; there the local picture goes blind. Chapter 6 returns to
    what falls outside it.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 2</span>The cutoff, made smooth</h2>

  <p>
    The cutoff needs one piece of care. If a neighborhood simply stopped at a hard edge — inside
    counts, outside does not — then an atom drifting across that edge would pop in and out of the
    sum, and the energy would jump. Forces are slopes of the energy; a jump in the energy is an
    infinite force. That would wreck any simulation in a single step.
  </p>

  <p>
    So the boundary is a dimmer, not a switch. Each neighbor's contribution is multiplied by a
    <strong>cutoff function</strong> that fades to zero as the neighbor reaches the cutoff radius
    <em>r</em><sub>c</sub> — full weight up close, then easing off so gently that it arrives at zero
    with zero slope, no kink. An atom drifting across the boundary weighs nothing there and crosses
    smoothly, so neither the energy nor the force — itself a slope — ever jumps. The cutoffs are
    small: five or six ångströms, far enough to take in an atom's nearest neighbors and the ring or
    two beyond.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <div class="fig-frame">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 280" role="img" aria-label="A central atom with a cutoff sphere: neighbors inside are connected to it, neighbors outside are not, and a cutoff function fades smoothly to zero slope at the radius.">
        <circle cx="200" cy="150" r="120" fill="none" stroke="var(--oxblood)" stroke-width="1" />
        <text x="200" y="24" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">cutoff radius rᶜ ≈ 5 Å</text>

        <g stroke="var(--rule)" stroke-width="1">
          <line x1="200" y1="150" x2="140" y2="110" />
          <line x1="200" y1="150" x2="250" y2="110" />
          <line x1="200" y1="150" x2="160" y2="205" />
          <line x1="200" y1="150" x2="270" y2="180" />
          <line x1="200" y1="150" x2="130" y2="180" />
        </g>
        <g fill="var(--ink)">
          <circle cx="140" cy="110" r="6" />
          <circle cx="250" cy="110" r="6" />
          <circle cx="160" cy="205" r="6" />
          <circle cx="270" cy="180" r="6" />
          <circle cx="130" cy="180" r="6" />
        </g>
        <circle cx="200" cy="150" r="8" fill="var(--oxblood)" />

        <circle cx="316" cy="150" r="6" fill="var(--ink)" opacity="0.4" />
        <text x="322" y="170" class="svg-small" opacity="0.7">at the edge: weight ≈ 0</text>

        <g fill="none" stroke="var(--ink-3)" stroke-width="1.2">
          <circle cx="360" cy="84" r="6" />
          <circle cx="372" cy="214" r="6" />
          <circle cx="318" cy="250" r="6" />
        </g>
        <text x="372" y="234" class="svg-small">outside: ignored</text>

        <!-- inset: cutoff function, flat at both ends -->
        <line x1="478" y1="64" x2="478" y2="214" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="0.75" />
        <line x1="478" y1="214" x2="694" y2="214" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="0.75" />
        <text x="472" y="74" text-anchor="end" class="svg-small">weight</text>
        <text x="472" y="86" text-anchor="end" class="svg-small">1</text>
        <text x="694" y="232" text-anchor="end" class="svg-serif-it">distance →</text>
        <path d="M 482 82 C 560 82, 600 212, 656 212 L 690 212" fill="none" stroke="var(--oxblood)" stroke-width="2" />
        <line x1="656" y1="210" x2="656" y2="218" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="0.75" />
        <text x="656" y="230" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">rᶜ</text>
      </svg>
    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 2</span>An atom's cutoff. Neighbors inside the radius count toward its energy; atoms outside are ignored. The weight does not drop off a cliff at <em>r</em><sub>c</sub> — it eases to zero with zero slope (inset), so an atom crossing the boundary never makes the energy or the force jump.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 3</span>Atoms as a graph</h2>

  <p>
    Locality has a natural shape, and it gives the chapter its name. Draw every atom as a node. Draw
    an edge between two atoms whenever they fall within the cutoff of each other. What you get is a
    <strong>graph</strong> — and it is exactly the data structure the machinery of the next chapter
    runs on. The same neighborhood can be drawn as the ball-and-stick picture a chemist sketches, or
    as this graph of nodes and edges, or as a plain table of the distances between every pair. They
    carry the same information; the graph is the form the model works in — a map of who-is-near-whom,
    not who-is-bonded-to-whom.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <div class="fig-frame">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 230" role="img" aria-label="The same four-atom group drawn two ways: as a ball-and-stick molecule, and as an abstract graph of nodes and edges.">
        <text x="160" y="40" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">ball-and-stick</text>
        <g stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="2">
          <line x1="110" y1="140" x2="170" y2="100" />
          <line x1="110" y1="140" x2="170" y2="180" />
          <line x1="170" y1="100" x2="220" y2="140" />
          <line x1="170" y1="180" x2="220" y2="140" />
        </g>
        <g fill="var(--ink)">
          <circle cx="110" cy="140" r="9" />
          <circle cx="170" cy="100" r="9" />
          <circle cx="170" cy="180" r="9" />
          <circle cx="220" cy="140" r="9" />
        </g>

        <text x="360" y="120" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif" style="font-size:20px;">→</text>

        <text x="555" y="40" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-label">graph</text>
        <g stroke="var(--rule)" stroke-width="1.2">
          <line x1="505" y1="140" x2="565" y2="100" />
          <line x1="505" y1="140" x2="565" y2="180" />
          <line x1="565" y1="100" x2="615" y2="140" />
          <line x1="565" y1="180" x2="615" y2="140" />
          <line x1="565" y1="100" x2="565" y2="180" />
        </g>
        <g fill="var(--paper)" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.5">
          <circle cx="505" cy="140" r="8" />
          <circle cx="565" cy="100" r="8" />
          <circle cx="565" cy="180" r="8" />
          <circle cx="615" cy="140" r="8" />
        </g>
        <line x1="556" y1="108" x2="574" y2="172" stroke="var(--oxblood)" stroke-width="1.2" />
        <text x="640" y="140" class="svg-small">edge within</text>
        <text x="640" y="152" class="svg-small">cutoff, not a bond</text>
      </svg>
    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 3</span>The same group of atoms as a molecule and as a graph (and, just as well, as a table of pairwise distances). One caution: an edge means "within the cutoff," not "chemically bonded." The cutoff runs several bond lengths, so an atom is joined to many neighbors it shares no bond with — the oxblood edge here is one of them.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 4</span>Describing a patch without coordinates</h2>

  <p>
    We have each atom's neighborhood; how do we hand it to the function without the raw coordinates
    that doomed the naive attempt? Describe each neighbor by three things that survive all three
    symmetries: its <strong>distance</strong> from the central atom, the <strong>angles</strong> it
    makes with the other neighbors, and its <strong>element</strong>. Distances and angles do not
    change when the molecule is slid or turned; an element stays itself however the molecule is
    placed or labeled. And because each neighbor's term carries its element, adding the neighbors up
    in any order leaves the patch unchanged — there is the permutation symmetry.
  </p>

  <p>
    Distances, angles, and species still do not pin a neighborhood down completely — that takes a
    little more, and supplying it is part of the network's job next chapter — but they are the
    backbone of every description that follows.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 5</span>Invariant energy, equivariant forces</h2>

  <p>
    The energy is a single number, and turning the molecule does not change it. A quantity that
    ignores the rotation this way is <strong>invariant</strong>. Think of a bathroom scale: turn the
    scale on the floor and the weight it reads is the same.
  </p>

  <p>
    The force is not a number but an arrow — a direction and a strength on each atom. Turn the
    molecule and every force arrow turns rigidly with it, keeping its grip on each atom. A quantity
    that turns along with the system is <strong>equivariant</strong>. In symbols, rotate the whole
    system by a rotation <em>R</em> and the energy <em>E</em> is unchanged, while each force
    <em>f</em> becomes <em>R f</em> — turned by the same <em>R</em>.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <div class="fig-frame">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 280" role="img" aria-label="A molecule with force arrows on its atoms, and the same molecule rotated: the force arrows rotate with it while the energy reading is unchanged.">
        <g stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="2">
          <line x1="130" y1="170" x2="210" y2="170" />
          <line x1="130" y1="170" x2="170" y2="100" />
          <line x1="210" y1="170" x2="170" y2="100" />
        </g>
        <g fill="var(--ink)">
          <circle cx="130" cy="170" r="8" />
          <circle cx="210" cy="170" r="8" />
          <circle cx="170" cy="100" r="8" />
        </g>
        <g stroke="var(--oxblood)" stroke-width="1.6">
          <line x1="130" y1="170" x2="113" y2="190" marker-end="url(#frc)" />
          <line x1="210" y1="170" x2="227" y2="190" marker-end="url(#frc)" />
          <line x1="170" y1="100" x2="170" y2="76" marker-end="url(#frc)" />
        </g>
        <text x="170" y="238" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif-it">E = −4.21 eV</text>

        <line x1="300" y1="150" x2="396" y2="150" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.2" marker-end="url(#rot)" />
        <text x="348" y="140" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-small">rotate</text>

        <g stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="2">
          <line x1="497" y1="140" x2="558" y2="191" />
          <line x1="497" y1="140" x2="572" y2="112" />
          <line x1="558" y1="191" x2="572" y2="112" />
        </g>
        <g fill="var(--ink)">
          <circle cx="497" cy="140" r="8" />
          <circle cx="558" cy="191" r="8" />
          <circle cx="572" cy="112" r="8" />
        </g>
        <g stroke="var(--oxblood)" stroke-width="1.6">
          <line x1="497" y1="140" x2="474" y2="144" marker-end="url(#frc)" />
          <line x1="558" y1="191" x2="558" y2="214" marker-end="url(#frc)" />
          <line x1="572" y1="112" x2="586" y2="95" marker-end="url(#frc)" />
        </g>
        <text x="535" y="245" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif-it">E = −4.21 eV</text>

        <defs>
          <marker id="frc" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="4" orient="auto"><path d="M0 0 L8 4 L0 8 z" fill="var(--oxblood)" /></marker>
          <marker id="rot" markerWidth="9" markerHeight="9" refX="7" refY="4.5" orient="auto"><path d="M0 0 L9 4.5 L0 9 z" fill="var(--ink)" /></marker>
        </defs>
      </svg>
    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 4</span>Same molecule, rotated. The energy reading is identical — invariant — while every force arrow has turned with the molecule — equivariant.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    Because the force is the slope of the energy — <em>F</em> = −∇<em>E</em> — a properly invariant
    energy yields properly equivariant forces the instant you differentiate it. Get the energy's
    symmetry right and the forces' comes free. Whether to let rotation live <em>inside</em> the
    network's hidden workings, not only at its input and output, is the heart of the next chapter.
  </p>

  <p>
    The shape of the machine is now visible. Cut the energy into local per-atom pieces, which makes
    the atoms a graph. Describe each atom's patch by distances, angles, and species, which slide,
    turn, and relabel without changing. Add the pieces for an invariant energy; differentiate for
    equivariant forces. One box is still shut: the per-atom function ε<sub>i</sub> itself — how a
    neighborhood becomes a number. Opening that box is the next chapter, and it is where the learning
    actually happens.
  </p>

